   N-15 and delta O-18(NO3), with a epsilon N/epsilon O ratio of 1.8,
   consistent with denitrification processes. The link between
   denitrification and pyrite oxidation is demonstrated by coupling
   chemical data with nitrate and sulfate isotopes. Furthermore, a spatial
   distribution of samples with significant denitrification was observed,
   allowing us to determine two main hydrogeological zones where natural
   attenuation was most effective. In several of the studied points,
   denitrification processes related to pyrite oxidation predominated and
   an estimation of the isotopic enrichment factors was performed using the
   temporal variations of nitrate concentration and the isotopic
   composition of dissolved nitrate (delta N-15(NO3) and delta O-18(NO3)).
   Finally, using estimated isotopic enrichment factors, an approximation
   of the degree of natural attenuation of nitrate was performed on those
   samples showing clear denitrification, and a median value of 30\% of
   contaminant diminution was obtained. (C) 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights
