Year = {{2009}},
Pages = {{185-213}},
Abstract = {{Monitoring forest cover change and understanding the dynamics of forest
   is increasingly important in sustainable management of forest
   ecosystems. This paper uses temporal MODIS Vegetation Continuous Field
   (MODIS 44B-VCF) to monitor tree cover change over Indian region for a
   period of 6 years (2000 - 2005). Pixel based linear regression model is
   used to identify changes in the form of slope, offset and variance.
   These inputs were stacked and classified using threshold method into
   forest and non-forest classes, Which resulted in pixel change as
   no-change and the change areas as positive and negative respectively.
   MODIS-VCF raw product of 2005 was validated using field data gathered in
   different tree crown cover as part of Department of Space Department of
   Biotechnology (DOS-DBT) Biodiversity characterization at landscape level
   project and the results shows a reasonable relationship (86.6\%) between
   tree canopy cover with tree crown cover. The change pixels were masked
   with GLCF land-cover map to estimate percent tree cover change within
   the forest region for further assessment. Results were overlaid with
   UNEP protected area boundary for the application of natural resource
   management and wildlife protection. On a long-term basis, the forest
   cover change was monitored using high spatial resolution (Landsat and
   IRS LISS-III) satellite data (1972 - 2005) to identify rates of
   deforestation and fragmentation at landscape level for sustaining the
   region's biodiversity and managing the forest ecosystems. The current
   study proposes Rapid Ecological Alerts (RET's) using the forest area
   change and this approach can be automated for every year.}},
