   Max-Neefs; `threshold hypothesis'. After a brief review of the criticism
   that the ISEW has attracted over the years, the paper then explains and
   discusses the rationale for omitting the `net capital growth' and
   `change in net international investment position' items. It is argued
   that these items do not comply with the theoretical foundation
   underpinning the ISEW. The paper also puts forward new valuation methods
   for several items within the index: the escalation factor in the
   valuation of natural capital depletion is dropped, long-term
   environmental damage is valued using a stock-based approach and
   considerably more government expenditures are considered to be
   non-defensive. The results of the `revised' ISEW show significant
   improvements in sustainable economic welfare over the entire study
