Title = {{Metapopulations in multifractal landscapes: on the role of spatial
   aggregation}},
Journal = {{PROCEEDINGS OF THE ROYAL SOCIETY B-BIOLOGICAL SCIENCES}},
Year = {{2005}},
Volume = {{272}},
Number = {{1574}},
Pages = {{1815-1822}},
Month = {{SEP 7}},
Abstract = {{The use of fractals in ecology is currently pervasive over many areas.
   However, very few studies have linked fractal properties of landscapes
   to generating ecological mechanisms and dynamics. In this study I show
   that lacunarity (a measure of the landscape texture) is a well suited
   ecologically scaled landscape index that can be explicitly incorporated
   in metapopulation models such as the classical Levins equation. I show
   that the average lacunarity of an aggregated landscape is linearly
   correlated to the habitat that a species with local spatial processed
   information may perceive. Lacunarity is a computationally feasible index
   to measure, and is related to the metapopulation capacity of landscapes.
   A general approach to multiftactal landscapes has been conceived, and
   some analytical results for self-similar landscapes are outlined,
   including the specific effect of landscape heterogeneity, decoupled from
   that of contagion by dispersal. Spatially explicit simulations show
   agreement with the semi-implicit method presented.}},
