Title = {{A biological method for the calculation of a safety index for monitoring
   sludge discharge}},
Journal = {{FRESENIUS ENVIRONMENTAL BULLETIN}},
Year = {{2000}},
Volume = {{9}},
Number = {{5-6}},
Pages = {{257-264}},
Month = {{MAY-JUN}},
Note = {{10th International Symposium of MESAEP, ALICANTE, SPAIN, OCT 02-06, 1999}},
Abstract = {{The discharge of industrial wastes is subject to strict regulations and
   controls. In many cases where a verification of the relative safety
   level is required, biological assays carried out on microorganisms,
   invertebrates have been proposed as means of assessing the global
   harmlessness of wastes towards living beings. However, the universal
   validity of some of these tests is questionable and it is generally
   accepted that more tests are needed in order to ensure a higher standard
   of safety with respect to higher vertebrates and humans.
   Another problem arises when certain low-toxicity wastes are generated in
   vast quantities, such as decanted sludge from sewage pipes. fortunately,
   it is possible in many cases to scatter these wastes on cultivable soils
   as fertilizer after being verified harmless. For that purpose, we have
   developed a test which utilizes human cells (HT29 cell-line from human
   gut mucosa) in culture.
   The measured growth rate of these cells after a 24 hr-exposure to
   filtration-sterilized sludge samples is taken as an index of any
   cellular insult. The fact that tests are carried out on naked cells in
   culture flasks (96 wells plates) is likely to permit the detection of
   any noxious effect with the highest sensitivity. In order to improve
   rapidity and sensitivity of the test, growth rate was estimated by
   incorporating a colorimetric assay for total proteins (using
   sulforhodamine B) directly into the culture plates. The test was then
   applied to actual decanted sludge from water-treatment plants.
   It appears that sludge stimulates cell growth before having a negative
   effect for higher concentration, indicating that sludges are not highly
   toxic products.
   Our biological test integrates all chemical agents as well as all
   possible synergistic effects which could impair cell growth, our values
   represent the maximal potential harmful effect on the environment. From
   the threshold of concentration which does not affect cell growth, we
   have calculated a numeric ``safety index{''} expressed as t/ha/yr which
   indicates the amount of sludge which can be dispersed, as a fertilizer,
   per hectare of agricultural soils.}},
