Month = {{MAR-APR}},
Abstract = {{The emission of malodorous gaseous compounds from wastewater collection
   and treatment facilities is a growing maintenance and environmental
   problem. Numerous gaseous compounds with low odor detection thresholds
   are emitted from these facilities. Sulfur-bearing gases represent
   compounds with the lowest odor detection threshold. Using solid
   adsorbent preconcentration and gas chromatographic methods, the quantity
   and composition of reduced malodorous sulfur gases emitted from various
   steps of the treatment process were determined in wastewater treatment
   plants in Baron Rouge, Louisiana. Hydrogen sulfide, which is a
   malodorous, corrosive, and potentially toxic gas, was the most dominant
   volatile reduced sulfur (S) compound measured (concentration range:
   0.017 to 446.9 mu g S/L). Concentrations were not only more than the
   odor detection threshold of hydrogen sulfide, but above levels that may
   affect health during longterm exposure. The concentrations of
   methanethiol (0.008 to 8.7 mu g S/L), dimethyl sulfide (0.003 8 to 26.4
   mu g S/L), carbon disulfide (0.006 to 5.70 mu g S/L), and carbonyl
   sulfide (0.005 to 7.30 mu g S/L) were significantly less than hydrogen
   sulfide. However, even though emissions of reduced sulfur gases other
   than hydrogen sulfide were low, previous studies suggested that
   long-term exposure to such levels may cause respiratory problems and
   other symptoms.}},
